Aortic Regurgitation: Total vs Forward Stroke Volume

Key concept: PV loops display total stroke volume (forward + regurgitant flow). Only forward SV contributes to effective cardiac output.

Relationship: Total SV = Forward SV + Regurgitant Volume

Example: Total SV 150 mL with 50% regurgitant fraction Forward SV 75 mL + Regurgitant 75 mL (returns to LV during diastole).

Clinical takeaway: A large PV loop does not guarantee high cardiac outputforward SV may be markedly reduced despite wide loops.

Chronic overload: Severe AR (>50% regurgitant fraction) causes eccentric hypertrophy and progressive LV dilation.

Aortic Stenosis: Pressure Overload Physiology

Key concept: The LV faces increased afterload from a stenotic valve, requiring higher systolic pressures to eject blood.

EDV: Typically preserved in compensated AS.

ESV: Increases as the ventricle cannot fully empty, narrowing the PV loop.

Loop changes:
Taller, narrower loop
Peak LV pressure rises
Stroke volume declines
EDV ~same, ESV

Compensation: Concentric hypertrophy normalizes wall stress but eventually fails, causing symptoms (angina, syncope, dyspnea).

HFrEF PV Loop (Acute vs Chronic)

Acute is selected by default. Turn on Compare with Chronic to overlay both loops.

Key Concepts: Normal Cardiac Physiology

Preload (EDV): Ventricular filling prior to contraction; increased by venous return and atrial kick.

Afterload: Resistance the LV must overcome (approx. SVR); elevated levels reduce stroke volume.

Contractility: Intrinsic inotropic state independent of preload/afterload; enhanced by sympathetic tone and positive inotropes.

PV loop: Width = stroke volume, height = generated pressure, area stroke work.

Cardiac & Vascular Function Curves (Guyton Curves)
Key Concepts:
Cardiac Function (Red): Logarithmic curve - steep rise initially, then gradual flattening. Inotropy shifts UP and LEFT.
Venous Return (Blue): Linear descending. Volume shifts RIGHT (x-intercept). TPR = flatter slope.
Equilibrium (Green dot): Intersection = operating point where venous return equals cardiac output.

Reduced pumping ability with EF < 40%. The Frank-Starling curve is depressed and shifted downward. Compensatory mechanisms include tachycardia and fluid retention.

Thickened myocardium with diastolic dysfunction. Despite increased contractility, stroke volume is reduced due to impaired filling and possible outflow obstruction.

Pericardial fluid compresses the heart, severely restricting ventricular filling. This leads to equalization of diastolic pressures and decreased cardiac output.

Understanding Pathological States

Click any pathology card above to load its characteristic hemodynamic profile into the simulator. This will automatically switch to the Interactive Simulator tab with the pathology parameters loaded.

Pressure Overload (e.g., Aortic Stenosis): Increased afterload leads to concentric hypertrophy. The pressure-volume loop shows increased systolic pressures with maintained or reduced stroke volume.

Volume Overload (e.g., Mitral Regurgitation): Increased preload causes eccentric hypertrophy. The PV loop widens with increased end-diastolic volume.

Systolic Dysfunction (e.g., HFrEF): Reduced contractility shifts the Frank-Starling curve downward. Despite increased preload, stroke volume remains low.

Diastolic Dysfunction (e.g., HCM): Impaired relaxation reduces preload. The PV loop shows increased diastolic pressures with reduced ventricular filling.
